title: Asian-Style Peanut Butter Ramen with Spicy Orange Shrimp
summary: You can never have too many main course recipes, so give Asian-Style Peanut Butter Ramen with Spicy Orange Shrimp a try. Watching your figure? This dairy free and pescatarian recipe has 736 calories, 25g of protein, and 31g of fat per serving. For $1.57 per serving, this recipe covers 24% of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes roughly 30 minutes. Not a lot of people made this recipe, and 5 would say it hit the spot. Head to the store and pick up crystalized ginger, coleslaw mix, orange marmalade, and a few other things to make it today. To use up the ginger you could follow this main course with the Ginger Cake with Crystallized Ginger Frosting as a dessert. This recipe is typical of Japanese cuisine. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 68%. This score is pretty good. Try Asian-style noodles with spicy peanut sauce, Shrimp and Kale Stir Fry in a Spicy Asian Orange Sauce, and Amen for Ramen Asian Style Salad for similar recipes.

winePairing.pairingText: Ramen Noodles works really well with Riesling, Sake, and Sauvignon Blanc. Saké is an obvious choice when it comes to Japanese food. If you want to stick to grape wine, though, you might opt for sauvignon blanc or riesling. One wine you could try is Schloss Vollrads Riesling Spatlese. It has 4.4 out of 5 stars and a bottle costs about 33 dollars.

productMatches.title: Schloss Vollrads Riesling Spatlese
productMatches.description: Classic natural sweet Spatlese with nice acidity and elegant, natural residual sugar. Selective harvest, gentle processing of the must, systematic clarification, slow fermentation and careful finishing are the basics for this traditional Vollrads' Riesling.This wine pairs perfectly with Asian cuisine due to the harmony of sweetness and acidity. Also interesting taste combinations can be achieved through the pairing of blue-veined cheese or a fruit dessert.

instructions: In a medium bowl, whisk together the sriracha, marmalade, soy sauce, vinegar and grated ginger. Stir in the shrimp. Refrigerate 20 minutes.Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the onion and pepper and saute until tender. Add the garlic and cook 1 minute.Reduce the heat to medium-low and add the  cup coconut milk, peanut butter, teriyaki sauce, crystalized ginger, hot pepper flakes and brown sugar. Simmer for 2 to 3 minutes, adding additional coconut milk as needed.Reserve  cup of the sauce and add the ramen noodles to remaining sauce.In large skillet over medium heat, cook the shrimp 2 to 3 minutes on each side until tender. Move the shrimp to outer edge of pan and cook the coleslaw mix in the center just until it starts to wilt. Add the wilted slaw to the ramen sauce mixture. Add more of the reserved sauce, if needed. Serve topped with the cooked shrimp.
